    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:9a920839-d32e-4fd2-88c1-ba9b73465792",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 51-year-old Czech male of stocky build with a slightly ruddy complexion, presenting to his general practitioner in Brno complaining of diffuse muscle pain [SNOMED:M79.1] that has been troubling him for the past several weeks. He describes a dull, aching discomfort predominantly affecting the thighs, calves, and upper back, rated 5–6 out of 10 in severity, which worsens after prolonged sitting at his desk or following weekend hiking trips in the Moravian hills.\n\n{patientName} works as a civil engineer for a mid-sized construction firm, spending most of his day reviewing blueprints and attending site inspections. He commutes by car and acknowledges a largely sedentary weekday routine, compensated by enthusiastic weekend outdoor activities including hiking, cycling, and occasional cross-country skiing in winter. He is a non-smoker who socially drinks beer — roughly 3–4 pints per week — and eats a typical Central European diet heavy in pork, potatoes, and bread.\n\nHe lives in a flat in Brno with his wife and their teenage son. He describes himself as a moderately stressed but generally content individual; his close friend circle includes colleagues from work and neighbours he sees regularly. He reports disrupted sleep due to muscle discomfort at night, which has made him irritable and less focused at work.\n\nOn examination, {patientName} appears mildly overweight but otherwise in no acute distress. He winces with deep palpation of bilateral quadriceps and paraspinal muscles [SNOMED:M79.1]. There is no joint swelling, redness, or neurological deficit. He denies any fever, rash, or recent viral illness. Range of motion is preserved in all major joints."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:02e40429-c523-455d-af2f-d6f578c4f1c9",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has no prior hospitalizations and no known chronic diseases. He does not take any regular prescription medications. He has a history of mild hypertension managed with lifestyle measures only (diet and moderate exercise), identified during an occupational health check three years ago. He underwent a right knee arthroscopy in 2017 following a sports-related meniscal tear sustained during hiking. He completed a course of physical therapy post-operatively with good recovery.\n\n{patientName} reports that his muscle pain [SNOMED:M79.1] began insidiously approximately 6–8 weeks ago, initially attributed to increased hiking activity. However, he notes the pain persists even on rest days, which prompted him to seek medical attention. He denies previous episodes of similar pain. He does not use statins, corticosteroids, or other drugs known to cause myopathy. His BMI is approximately 27 kg/m². He acknowledges high occupational stress levels in recent months due to a large project deadline. He has no history of autoimmune disease, thyroid disorder, or diabetes. Family history is notable for ischaemic heart disease in his father and musculoskeletal complaints in his mother."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
